: In <holenCzELr5.rH@netcom.com> holen@netcom.com (Victor A. Holen ) 
: writes: 

: >Since the new mother-boards allow for memory with no parity, the
: >questions:
: >
: >Is there any benefit from buying the more expensive parity memory ?
: >Does (for example) Intel's Plato MB check parity if chips have it
: >and warns about errors ?
: >
: >Can any software access parity bits to verify and test memory ?
: >
: >-- 
: > victor      holen@netcom.com

: The parity bit is pretty much useless which is why Mac's never had it 
: and most new PC designs are moving away from it.

I most strongly disagree with these remarks. Only toy/game computers like
Macs, Amiga's, Atari's et al have no parity checked memory or other
memory reliability schemes.

Parity checking is the only way YOU, as a consumer have to make sure
the expensive SIMMs in your computer are working as advertised.

Disabling parity checking is used by disreputable PC dealers to
prevent service calls.  

The scheme works like this:

You buy a PC from an el-cheapo dealer (we are all looking for lowest 
prices aren't we?). Your PC happens to work quite well, but starting
1 hour after turning it on your Windows is far more likely to throw
a GP fault, killing your applications.

It is just as likely that these problems come from bad memory chips
as from faults in your software. Without parity check you will never
find out, and your dealer will happilly point out that Windows has 
a lot of bugs and he is not to blame.... go figure!

The techical explanation behind parity check is that on every 
memory write a 9th parity bit is generated for every 8-bit part
of the 32-bit memory word. This parity bit is generated in such a way as
to make the number of 1's in each 9 bit even. The parity bit is
written to that separate 9th bit chip on your SIMM's.

When reading from memory these parity bits are checked by the
memory circuitry (in hardware) to make sure the numer of 1's is still
even. If for any reason: bad chip, power fluctuation, overclocking,
alpha particles, cosmic rays etc. a bit flips the parity will come out
wrong and generate an error. Ignoring hardware parity errors means
that your computer programs generate erroneous results without you
ever knowing!!!

Of course, parity check is not infallibe, but the chance of having
correctly working memory is a lot higher.

You may point out that programs like 'Checkit' and even 'himem.sys'
can test your memory. This is true, but only so far. The problem is
that these programs will only catch hard memory errors, bits that are
really defective. These programs will never find the intermittent 
weak (defective) memory chip that happens to go wrong just when you
are running some critical application. Memory test programs cannot
access the memory like an operating system as UNIX, LINUX or even
MS-Windows does. Thus the need for hardware supported parity check.

It is easy to grade PC dealers:

Those who happily sell you a PC with 8-bit SIMMs and parity check 
disabled (naturally!) are to be avoided! This even includes some
major brands...

Saving on the parity bits gives them a 10% cost advantage
on memory chips and an easy way out in case of bad chips.

The morale: Don't buy toy computers.


P.S. Elsewhere in this newsgroup users are flaming Intel for not
telling the world about a FPU bug. I am wondering how many of these
users are running their PC without parity check, a far worse liability!
 

