This is the concept of 'fail-safe'.   If you're *depending* on the results to
be 'correct', you'll willingly settle for the possible 'false positive' error
indication.   Also, even in the above situation, the 'error' *is* _real_-- it
*does* mean 'something failed' -- it is 'user error' to interpret it with the
meaning of 'what was retrieved is not what was stored'.

Look at the alternative -- _no_ indication, -even- *when* a failure occurs.

Me, I *LIKE* 'safety nets' and insurance policies.  I like parity memory (if
I can't have ECC), for the same reasons. Murphy's Law is too prevalent in the
real world! :)

I also have real-world experience with main-memory parity errors -- I use a
*BIG* PC box, that has 32mb of ram, 2.5 gig of hard-disk, and is on 7 days, 
24 hours a day. I *do* see parity errors -- it averages approx. 1 per 15000 
hours of run-time.  Or 1-in-500-BILLION byte-hours.  close enough to zero
not to matter, right??  But I'm running mathematical modeling/simulations that
may run for several *weeks* of continuous computing.  All of a sudden its 
a '1-in-50' or so, chance that a given run might get clobbered by such an
error.  Now it matters!!


