I don't want to say that an Amiga or Mac is a not a usable computer,
but the main point is that without parity checked memory or other
reliability scheme you can't be sure your memory is operating correctly
all the time, so these computers are generally less trustworthy in
critical applications.

There have been many examples in the past of bad memory batches,
And because the density of SIMMs keeps increasing and competition is
cutthroat it surely will happen again!

Their manufacturers put that 10% price difference on memory costs and
simpler mainboard circuitry in their fat pockets.
:  
