: > Rietkerkweg 364					paul@pphbau.hobby.nl

: All you have to do is set the memory test program to run for about 24 hours.

Memory test programs access memory in a far more regular way than most 
operating systems, thus only approximating the computing load and random
effects of running your applications. I don't doubt that some memory test
programs are better than others, but I have never found an intermittent
parity failure with any of them.

Programs like Checkit are generally bought for the peace of mind.

As an historical example the Z80 chip needed a shorter access time
when executing instructions from memory than for reading/writing data.
Needless to say that on some memory boards you could read/write data
all day long without problems, but boy when you tried to run a program
in them!


: What if your parity circuit had a problem?  You could think that your
: RAM was intermittent when it is actually something else.

Now you are wide open. The whole point of having parity circuitry
is to find out if something is wrong! Even if the parity bit of
one of my SIMM's is defective or the motherboard parity circuitry
is bad I want to be told! What guarantee do I have that the other
memory chips on the SIMM's coming from the same batch do not develop
similar problems tomorrow? Or what guarantee do I have that only
the parity circuitry in ome of my motherboard ASIC's is affected?
   
If a fault develops in either of them I would replace all failing
components, including the motherboard if necessary.

Of course, you could switch off parity checking in your CMOS setup
and keep on running without safety net. Just like driving a car
without brakes.

The major point of this discussion is that parity checked RAM
is a good thing that really enhances the reliability of your computer
and gives you some protection from disreputable PC-dealers.
