See what I mean? The military doesn't trust computers without a memory
reliability scheme either.

: While parity checking does have value, it really is somewhat outdated.  I
: understand that parity checking will detect roughly 50-60 % of memory errors.
: Something like a CRC check is more reliable.

You are right! However, the main use of parity is to find out about
defective/failing components. If a memory chip is failing then it will
surely affect the parity check.

There are more elaborate memory reliability schemes like Hamming codes,
these allow detection and _correction_ of memory errors, but you need
far more additional bits and more elaborate circuitry to do this,
so these techniques are generally used on mainframe computers with 
very large memories where the probability of having a memory fault
would otherwise approach 1.

: I personally use parity RAM, but this still doesn't guarantee that bad RAM
: will be detected.

You have no guarantee that any memory fault will be detected, but a
defective RAM will be found immediately.

