	A lot of you seem to be missing the point.  You can have
perfectly fine memory no problems, and your memory can be changed
accidentaly by radiation flying in and whapping one of your bits
in you RAM.  Your memory will be fine before, during, and after
this whapping, but now it contains the wrong information.  Shielding
your memory from radiation will not prevent this either (it may
help) since the chips are slightly radioactive, as is everything,
mostly due to potassium being blasted by the sun's radiation in
the upper atmosphere, and changing into a radioactive isotope.
So, if you are running a critical process, especially one that
has a lot of memory, and /or takes a long time, you need error
correcting memory, that is capable of changing the whapped bit
back to its correct setting, on the fly with out any user intervention.
Memory parity will detect this whapped bit, and halt the system
to prevent you from running your computer on a process on wrong
data (big waste of time).  On computers with no parity checking,
or error correction memory, once your bit is whapped, you are
going to get a wrong answer, and you won't know it, and in critical
applications, this is not acceptable.

	Note, the above memory problems mentioned above have
nothing, NOTHING to do with faulty SIMMs.  Faulty SIMMs are
PHYSICALLY defective, and they don't work because they are
broken, replace them.  The memory problems in the previous
paragraph are soft memory errors, and are not, I repeat, NOT
due to broken RAM, and your RAM will not broken after this
happens either. Don't replace your RAM because you get one
parity error in a blue moon, it just happens.  If you have
a problem with getting parity errors once in a blue moon,
get acomputer with no parity checking (something like
walking around a minefield) or get a computer with error
correcting memory (something like sitting on a beach with
a beautiful man/woman (your choice) feeding you peeled 
grapes)

	Chris


