>From: mjscott@jones.heart.rri.uwo.ca (Mike J. Scott)
>Subject:Re: Parity. Anything checks it ?
>Date: 25 Nov 1994 17:26:15 GMT
>Message-ID:<3b56nn$en2@falcon.ccs.uwo.ca>

>While parity checking does have value, it really is somewhat outdated.  I
>understand that parity checking will detect roughly 50-60 % of memory errors.

I see this claim often, and I am mystified by it.

Many kinds of memory errors have independent probability of individual
bits being corrupted.  This means that if I have a probability of 10^-15
of a bit being wrong on a given access, I have a probability of only
36 * 10^-30 of exactly two bits being wrong in any given access to some
9-bit byte ( 36 = C(9,2), the number of ways of choosing 2 bits out of 9 ).

So I have a 1 in 10^15 chance of a single-bit (detectable) error and
a 36 in 10^30 chance of a double-bit (undetectable) error.

Note that this does not apply to all kinds of memory errors - just many
kinds. For example, if I have an error in which a given byte returns all
zeros regardless of what I try to store there, it will always pass a check
for even parity.

I would venture a guess that most soft memory errors are caught by parity
checks - assuming you have parity and it is enabled.

>Something like a CRC check is more reliable.

Absolutely.  On a PC-class machine it may be overkill, however, for there
are still portions of the system that are not subject to checks, including,
they tell me, floating point processors!

