: 	Hmmm, I knew its was the radioactivity, and I assumed it
: was potassium, since it is quite prevalent.  Thanks for the new
: info.  By the way what kind of levels of uranium and thorium
: are found in typical (if there is such a thing) packaging materials?

Ceramic packages are usually made of alumina (aluminum oxide), mixed
in with variou filler materials. Sealing glasses used to seal some
packages (CerDIPs) are mostly lead oxides mixed with all kinds of
other stuff. Plastic packages are typically epoxy resin, but with
various filler materials (used to adjust properties like expansion
coefficient).

Anyway, in 1977, when the problem was first identified, sealing
glasses were quite "hot," with more than 100 ppm uranium or thorium or
their various radioactive daughters. Ceramics were about 3-10 ppm
U/Th, about what ordinary topsoil is (granite is somewhat higher, and
I measured the volcanic ash of Mt. St. Helens at about 3 ppm).
Plastics were about 1 ppm, mostly due to the fillers at that time.

As years passed, vendors were forced to use purer materials, to avoid
certain types of fillers, etc. And nearly all DRAMs are in plastic
packages, which can be made very low in alpha emissions. (For example,
less than 0.05 ppm. Maybe even better by now.)

There's a lot I'm not getting into here, such as the relation between
ppm and alphas/cm^2-hour, device sensitivity, etc.

But this should be enough to get started. Lots of papers were
published on this, between 1978 and 1982. A fair number since, but
mostly on cosmic ray effects and non-package sources.

